{{出典の明記|date=2020-04-04}} [[File:Ogata Kenzan - Incense Box - Walters 49354 - Closed.jpg|thumb|200px|{{ill|Ogata Kenzan|ja|尾形乾山|12=draft}}'s incense box]] [[File:BLW Circular Box and Cover for Incense Woods.jpg|thumb|200px|Wooden incense box]] '''Kōgō''' (香合) refers to a small li11ed {{ill|container|ja|容器|12=draft}} for storing {{ill|incense|ja|香|12=draft}}. It is a type of {{ill|Japanese tea utensils|lt=tea utensil|ja|茶道具|1=Japanese tea utensils|lt=tea utensils|en|12=draft}} and also a kind of {{ill|Buddhist altar fitting|ja|仏具|12=draft}}. It can also be written as '''Kōbuta''' (香蓋) as an alternative spelling or referred to as '''Gōsu''' or '''Gōshi''' (合子).
== Kōgō in Tea Ceremony == In the tea ceremony, a kōgō is a container used for holding incense. During a tea gathering, incense is burned in the tea room, and the kōgō serves as the container for the incense. The kōgō is an important element in tea gatherings, and during the charcoal preparation ceremony, guests may request to view the kōgō. The kōgō typically contains three pieces of incense: two are placed near the charcoal to release fragrance, while one is set aside for the viewing. As with all tea utensils, the kōgō used depends on the season and the specific tea setting, with different kōgō being used for the brazier (炉) and hearth (風炉).
* {{ill|Censer|ja|香炉|12=draft}} (November to April) : Contains {{ill|Nerikō|ja|練香|12=draft}} (kneaded incense). Ceramic kōgō are used, as the moisture from nerikō can damage lacquerware, which is avoided in this case.
* {{ill|Furo (tea ceremony)|ja|風炉|12=draft}} (May to October) : Contains square-cut pieces of {{ill|incense wood|ja|香木|12=draft}}. Kōgō made from {{ill|karaki|ja|唐木|12=draft}} or bamboo lacquerware are used.
* Year-round : Includes clamshell kōgō (e.g., {{ill|clam|ja|ハマグリ|12=draft}}, {{ill|sunset clam|ja|ツキヒガイ|12=draft}}) or metal kōgō.
== Kōgō in Buddhist Altar Fittings == In Buddhist rituals, kōgō are generally used for holding {{ill|shōkō|ja|焼香|12=draft}} (powdered incense) or {{ill|makkō|ja|抹香|12=draft}}. They may also be used as containers for {{ill|zukkō|ja|塗香|12=draft}} (powdered perfume).
